+---
+title: Execution patterns
+description: How queue-level execution patterns (static-dag, pipeline, map-reduce) layer above the tick engine — the extendRun seam, run.extended audit entries, the gate/respawn circle-back, and the forward-arc-never-rewind invariant.
+---
+
+The core tick engine described in [How an offload run executes](/agora/explanation/how-offload-runs/)
+handles one responsibility: advancing a fixed DAG of **WorkItems** through their
+status lattice. Execution patterns are a separate layer built *on top of* that
+engine — they let a queue answer a richer question: "now that some items have
+finished, should the run grow?" This page explains the pattern layer, how you
+configure it per queue, and the invariants that keep dynamically grown graphs
+safe and auditable.
+
+## What execution patterns are
+
+An **execution pattern** is a per-queue strategy object that the orchestrator
+consults once per tick, *after* the engine has advanced item states. The pattern
+inspects the terminal items of every unsealed run on the queue and may return a
+set of new **WorkItem** descriptors to append. Three patterns ship in the engine:
+
+- **`static-dag`** — the default; the pattern layer is a no-op. The run's DAG is
+  fully specified at submit time and never changes.
+- **`pipeline`** — items flow through a sequence of named stages. When a gate item
+  finishes, the pattern can spawn the next stage's items or, on failure, spawn a
+  remediation branch and circle back (see [Gate/respawn below](#gaterespawn-the-pipeline-circle-back)).
+- **`map-reduce`** — a splitter item writes its outputs to a well-known path; the
+  pattern reads those output names and spawns one map item per output, then
+  spawns the reduce item only once all map items are done.
+
+All three reuse the identical engine. The pattern layer is purely an *item
+producer* — it has no scheduling authority and no visibility into `running` items.
+Scheduling, locking, and concurrency remain the engine's job.
+
+## Queue-level pattern config
+
+Patterns are configured in `agora.config.ts` on the queue definition, not on
+individual runs. A queue without a `pattern` key defaults to `static-dag`
+transparently.
+
+```ts
+// agora.config.ts
+export default defineConfig({
+  queues: [
+    {
+      name: 'nightly',
+      concurrency: 4,
+      pattern: {
+        type: 'map-reduce',
+        splitterExecutor: 'file-splitter',
+        mapExecutor:      'chunk-processor',
+        reduceExecutor:   'aggregator',
+      },
+    },
+    {
+      name: 'ci',
+      concurrency: 2,
+      pattern: {
+        type: 'pipeline',
+        stages: ['build', 'test', 'deploy'],
+        gateExecutor: 'stage-gate',
+      },
+    },
+  ],
+});
+```
+
+The `pattern` object is validated at `serve` startup — a misconfigured pattern
+is a fatal startup error, not a per-run runtime failure. This makes the queue's
+contract visible to operators before any run is submitted.
+
+At runtime the orchestrator holds a `PatternRegistry` keyed by queue name. After
+every `tick()` call on a queue, the orchestrator looks up the pattern for that
+queue (if any) and runs the **pattern phase**: one call to
+`pattern.deriveSpawns(run, terminalItems)`. The call is pure — the pattern
+receives a snapshot of the current run graph and the items that just reached a
+terminal state; it returns a (possibly empty) list of spawn directives.
+
+## The `extendRun` seam
+
+Spawn directives from the pattern phase are not applied directly. They flow
+through **`extendRun`**, the single audited gateway for all post-submit
+mutations to a run:
+
+1. **Validate.** The proposed new items are merged with the existing run graph
+   and passed through the same `validateRun` call used at submit time. Any
+   item that references a non-existent dependency, introduces a lock with an
+   invalid key, or conflicts with an existing item id causes the entire spawn
+   batch to be rejected — the run continues without the new items, and the
+   error is recorded in the audit log.
+2. **Write.** Valid items are inserted into the run's item table with status
+   `pending`. The run transitions back out of any near-settled state.
+3. **Audit.** For each spawned item, `extendRun` writes a `run.extended` audit
+   entry that records:
+   - the spawned item's id,
+   - the **cause item** — the terminal item whose completion triggered the spawn,
+   - the actor `pattern:<queue-name>`, and
+   - the directive's content-addressed ref.
+
+The `run.extended` entries are first-class members of the audit bundle, so
+`agora verify` can reconstruct exactly *why* each dynamically added item exists
+— which cause item produced it, through which pattern, at which tick.
+
+Because `extendRun` runs **before** the seal check in the same tick, a run that
+just grew structurally cannot seal that tick. The seal check sees the freshly
+inserted `pending` items and defers. This guarantees that a run never seals with
+phantom-unseen items — the engine always drains what the pattern produced before
+declaring the run complete.
+
+## `run.extended` audit entries
+
+```jsonc
+// excerpt from an audit bundle
+{
+  "type": "run.extended",
+  "runId": "nightly@2026-06-07T02:00:00Z",
+  "queueName": "nightly",
+  "actor": "pattern:nightly",
+  "causeItemId": "split",
+  "causeResultRef": "agora://ns/artifact/split-abc/sha256:deadbeef",
+  "spawnedItems": [
+    { "id": "map-chunk-0", "executor": "chunk-processor", "depends_on": ["split"] },
+    { "id": "map-chunk-1", "executor": "chunk-processor", "depends_on": ["split"] },
+    { "id": "map-chunk-2", "executor": "chunk-processor", "depends_on": ["split"] }
+  ]
+}
+```
+
+The `causeResultRef` links directly to the artifact that contained the outputs
+driving the spawn decision, so an auditor can verify that the map fan-out
+matches exactly what the splitter wrote — without trusting the orchestrator's
+in-memory state.
+
+## Gate/respawn: the pipeline circle-back
+
+The `pipeline` pattern introduces a named **gate item** between stages. When a
+gate item reaches terminal status the pattern inspects the result:
+
+- **`done`** — the stage passed; spawn the next stage's items, pointing their
+  `depends_on` at the gate item.
+- **`failed`** — the stage did not pass; spawn a **remediation branch** (a set
+  of fix-up items specific to the failure mode), then spawn a new gate item for
+  the *same* stage pointing its `depends_on` at the remediation tail.
+
+The second case is the **gate/respawn circle-back**: the pipeline "circles back"
+to re-attempt the same stage gate, but does so by appending *new* items to the
+run rather than by modifying or restarting existing ones. The failed gate item
+remains permanently in the history as `failed`; the remediation items and the
+new gate item extend the run forward.
+
+```mermaid
+stateDiagram-v2
+  direction LR
+  [*]          --> build
+  build        --> gate-1      : done
+  gate-1       --> test        : pattern spawns (done)
+  gate-1       --> fix-lint    : pattern spawns (failed)
+  fix-lint     --> gate-1b     : done
+  gate-1b      --> test        : pattern spawns (done)
+  test         --> gate-2
+  gate-2       --> deploy      : pattern spawns (done)
+  deploy       --> [*]
+```
+
+`gate-1` and `gate-1b` are distinct item ids — the graph gains edges forward
+only. The failed `gate-1` branch is sealed history.
+
+## The forward-arc-never-rewind invariant
+
+All of the above rests on one structural guarantee: **spawned items may only
+introduce edges that point backward at already-existing items. No new item may
+be pointed at by an existing item.**
+
+More precisely: `extendRun`'s validator checks that every `depends_on` in the
+spawn batch refers to an item id that is already present in the merged graph
+*before* this extension. It also checks that no item in the *existing* graph has
+a `depends_on` that names a newly spawned item. Together these two checks enforce
+a strict **forward arc** property — the graph can grow, but only by adding leaves
+and new sub-graphs downstream of existing leaves. Existing topology is immutable
+once written.
+
+This invariant is what keeps execution patterns safe:
+
+- **Acyclicity is preserved.** Because new items only point backward, and
+  existing items never point forward at new items, the merged graph cannot gain
+  a cycle. The engine's `depends_on` semantics rely on the DAG being acyclic;
+  the validator enforces this without a full cycle-detection scan — the
+  forward-arc rule is sufficient.
+- **Replay is deterministic.** Patterns are pure functions of the run snapshot.
+  Spawn ids are deterministic (the pattern derives them from the cause item id
+  and the queue name). `extendRun` skips any already-present id as a no-op. If
+  the orchestrator crashes mid-extension and re-runs the pattern phase, it
+  re-derives the same spawn directives and `extendRun` absorbs the duplicates
+  silently.
+- **Audit closure is total.** Because no existing item can point at a newly
+  spawned item, every product consumed by a spawned item was already recorded
+  before the extension. `agora verify`'s provenance-closure check can walk the
+  entire graph — including dynamically grown branches — using exactly the same
+  algorithm it applies to static DAGs.
+
+The invariant can be summarised as: **the past is append-only, the future is
+forward-only**. A pipeline circle-back is not a loop in the graph — it is a
+new lineage appended ahead of the failed branch, with no edge reaching backward
+into already-sealed history.
+
+## Interaction with sealing and the tick order
+
+The full per-tick order on a pattern-bound queue is:
+
+1. **Engine tick** — ready, reconcile, fire, cascade (unchanged).
+2. **Pattern phase** — `pattern.deriveSpawns(run, newlyTerminal)`.
+3. **`extendRun`** — validate, write, audit each spawn batch.
+4. **Seal check** — if nothing is `pending`, `ready`, or `running`, seal the
+   run and emit `run.sealed`.
+
+Steps 2–3 are skipped on `static-dag` queues. The seal check at step 4 always
+sees the post-extension state, so a run extended in step 3 defers sealing to a
+future tick.
+
+If the pattern phase produces no spawns (either because no items newly terminated
+this tick, or because all terminal items were already processed), steps 2–3 are
+a no-op and add no overhead beyond the pattern's `deriveSpawns` call, which is
+expected to be O(terminal items) and free of I/O.
